<section xml:id="lesson5_2" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
   <title>Mathematical Models</title>

<p>
What is a mathematical model?</p>

<p>
A mathematical model predicts the behavior of some predictable process, 
like dividing a pie between a group of people. In order to solve these problems mathematically, we need a few things:</p>
 <p>
    <ul>
      <li>Mathematical symbols to express the parts of the problem.</li>
      <li>Mathematical operations to follow to calculate the result.</li>
    </ul>
    </p>

<p>If those don’t exist, then people invent new symbols and define new operations that properly predict the observed behavior.
The main point is that the mathematics is derived from observations of the real world, not the other way around. </p>

<section xml:id="fractions_mathematical_model" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
   <title>Mathematical model for fractions</title>

<p>I'll explain this using a familiar mathematical model - fractions! Consider the following problem:</p>

<p>
<ul>
<li>You have a pie to share with three friends. </li>
<li>You cut it into 4 equal pieces.</li>
<li>Your friend exclaims, “Just because there are four of us, it doesn’t mean we need to eat the whole pie! I only want half that much!!” </li>
<li>How much of the pie will you give your friend? </li>
</ul>
</p>

<p> You are probably so used to solving problems like this, that you don't think about all the steps that go into solving it with fractions!
Let's explore those aspects.</p>

<p> Step 1: Representing fractional state:</p>

<p>
We say “one fourth,” which could translate to “if that were divided into 4 equal-sized parts, then I want one of them.” 
We also represent this mathematically with the number of parts you want (numerator) placed over the total number of parts 
(denominator) with a line in between. We can either display it with the numerator above the denominator with a horizontal line in 
between or a 1 to the left of the 4 with a diagonal line in between. However, you cannot display it 1\4.
</p>
<sidebyside widths="15% 25%" valign="top">
    
    <image source="L5.0-fractionstate.png" width="66%" />
    <image source="L5.0-fractionstate2.png" width="66%" />
</sidebyside>

<p>This allows us to more clearly state the problem:</p>

<p>
<ul>
<li>You have a pie to share with three friends. </li>
<li>You cut it into 4 equal pieces, each 1/4 of the pie.</li>
<li>Your friend exclaims, “Just because there are four of us, it doesn’t mean we need to eat the whole pie! I only want 1/2 a piece!!” </li>
<li>How much of the pie will you give your friend? </li>
</ul>
</p>

<p> Step 2: Performing opreations:</p>

<p>To multiply fractions, we perform this set of operations:</p>

<p>
<ul>
<li>Multiply the numerators. </li>
<li>Multiply the denominators.</li>
<li>Simplify if necessary </li>
</ul>
</p>

<p><image source="L5.0-fractionmult.png" width="66%" /></p>

<p>Now let’s consider a slightly different question:</p>

<p>
<ul>
<li>You brought two pies to a potluck, pecan pie and apple pie. </li>
<li>Both pies have the same radius, but the pecan pie is much more intense than the apple pie, 
so you cut smaller pieces; You cut the pecan pie into 10 pieces and the apple pie into 8 pieces. </li>
<li>It is time to gather your leftovers. The pecan pie has 5 pieces left, and the apple pie has 3 pieces left. </li>
<li>How much total pie is there left?</li>
</ul>
</p>

<p> To solve this, you would perform the following steps:</p>
<p>
<ul>
<li>Express the leftover pecan pie as a fraction: 5/10 </li>
<li> Simplify the pecan pie fraction to be 1/2 </li>
<li>Express the leftover apple pie as a fraction: 3/8</li>
<li>Add the fractions </li>
</ul>
</p>

<p>Easy-peasy lemon-squeezy, right? Addition is easier than multiplication, so adding these fractions should be a 
piece of cake (or pie), right? </p>

<p>To add fractions, we perform this set of operations:</p>
<p>
<ul>
<li>Find the least common denominator. </li>
<li>Multiply the first numerator by (LCD/1stdenominator)</li>
<li>Multiply the second numerator by (LCD/2nddenominator)</li>
<li>Add the numberators and retain the common denominator</li>
<li>Simplify if necessary </li>
</ul>
</p>

<p><image source="L5.0-fractionadd.png" width="66%" /></p>

<p> Need to switch out for the exact problem posed above</p>

<p> I know what you're thinking, "Now you just hold on a cotton-pickin' minute. That didn't seem easier at all!"
I must agree with you there. The important takeaway here is the following:</p>

<p> (make big somehow) The mathematical representation you use had advantages and disadvantages in terms of readiability vs computation difficulty.
Fractions are very easy to interpret visually, but they are harder to perform addition. Decimals are sometimes harder to interpret, but addition and 
multiplication are easier than with fractions.</p>

<p> We are going to see the same tradeoffs in representing quantum state and performing quantum operations. We are going to learn two 
ways to express state - one that clearly shows the probabilities, and another that corresponds with how to perform operations.</p>


